  "Idea": "We propose Causal Manifold Adversarial Refinement (CMAR), a novel framework that generates high-quality hard negative samples for time series contrastive learning by enforcing adversarial perturbations to adhere to learned causal-temporal dynamics in the latent space. While existing methods focus on geometric realism (e.g., smoothness, frequency content), CMAR advances the state of the art by incorporating *causal plausibility*—ensuring that generated negatives evolve according to the intrinsic differential structure of the underlying system. Our key insight is that truly informative hard negatives should not only be close in embedding space but must also represent feasible counterfactual trajectories under the system's dynamics. To achieve this, CMAR jointly learns a latent ODE-based trajectory encoder and a sparse causal graph over latent dimensions (using continuous-time Granger causality or Jacobian analysis from neural ODEs). During contrastive training, for each anchor time series, we sample an initial negative from a different class, encode it into the latent space, and apply gradient-based adversarial refinement—not freely, but constrained to the manifold defined by the learned ODE and causal graph. Specifically, the adversarial update direction is projected onto the tangent space of the latent ODE flow, and regularized via a causal consistency loss that penalizes violations of directed dependencies among latent variables. This ensures that even when pushed closer to the anchor embedding, the negative remains a solution to a valid (though perturbed) dynamical system. The refined latent is decoded and used in a modified InfoNCE loss. Crucially, the causal graph and ODE parameters are updated end-to-end using reconstruction and contrastive objectives, enabling co-adaptation between representation quality and causal fidelity. CMAR enables the model to confront subtle, dynamically consistent confounders—such as ECG signals with reversed depolarization sequences or industrial sensor traces with inverted feedback loops—that challenge true understanding rather than surface statistics. This leads to sharper, more generalizable representations, especially in low-data and cross-domain settings. Applications span medical monitoring (detecting anomalous heart rhythms that mimic normal ones under altered conduction pathways), predictive maintenance (identifying failure modes that follow alternative degradation trajectories), and climate modeling (evaluating models on physically possible but rare weather patterns). We validate CMAR on PhysioNet, UCR archive, and synthetic datasets generated from known ODEs (e.g., Lorenz attractor), showing superior performance in linear probing, few-shot classification, and robustness to distribution shift compared to SimCLR-TS, TS-TCC, CA-MLP, and ablated versions of LARTC.",
